Software Defined Radio - how does it work? Part 9

Hi, Habr.

In the previous part , the decoding of RDS signals for FM radio stations was considered, and the idea of ‚Äã‚Äãthe next article arose by itself - you need to make your own FM transmitter.

There will be two options - simple, and more complex, with RDS.



As in the previous cases, we will do all this in GNU Radio, without writing a single line of code. For those who are interested, continued under the cut.

So let's get started. Of course, for the tests we need SDR with the ability to transfer (HackRF, USRP, LimeSDR).

FM transmitter


The scheme of a simple transmitter is made in almost two clicks, and I hope, it does not present any difficulties in understanding. I use the WAV-file as the source, although if you wish, you can also use another source, for example a sound card input.



Actually, there are two key blocks in this scheme - the WBFM transmitter and the Resampler, which transforms the stream sampling rate. All values ‚Äã‚Äãof the sampling frequency must match each other, otherwise there will be an omission of samples, which by ear will be heard as clicks. The Multiply Const block is used to adjust the input level. It is also important not to confuse, GNU Radio has two different blocks for FM - WBFM and NBFM. We need exactly the first one, Wide Band FM. NFM modulation is used for portable radios.

In general, everything is simple, we start, it works. There are no UI-blocks in the scheme, so you can use it from the command line (more details in the 4th part ).

By the way, if you look at the spectrum, you can make sure that a simple mono signal is being transmitted, without any channels, pilot tones or anything else.



It is time to move to a more complex option.

RDS Transmitter


The scheme of the transmitter with RDS will of course be more complicated. Its original was taken from gr-rds examples with minor changes (the original version for Windows did not work, the ‚Äúcorrect‚Äù version is at the bottom of the article), let's consider what components it consists of.



(original full resolution )

The top third of the circuit is the RDS transmission. At the entrance there is an RDS-encoder, which, based on the available data (station name, country code, etc.) forms RDS-packets. Then the bitstream is subjected to differential coding , the idea of ‚Äã‚Äãwhich is to remove the repeating sequences of the form 001000001. Then the signal is processed and the carrier is modulated by it at 57KHz. The central part is the creation of sound. Here channels L + R and LR are formed. Below as a sound source is specified wav-file. Finally, the Add block adds all this together, and a pilot tone of 19 KHz and a second tone of 38 KHz are also added to the signal. All this total signal is sent to the frequency modulator, all of which is transmitted via SDR.

In theory, this scheme is not 100% complete, for example, there is no predistortion block, the phases of the 19, 38 and 57 KHz tones are not synchronized. On the other hand, to understand how sound is transmitted to the air in general, such a scheme is quite enough, those who wish can modify it themselves.

At startup, a window opens, some parameters can be changed.



There was a desire to test RDS with a real receiver, but it turned out that FM radio is already an atavism, and I don‚Äôt have it at home. Even in the latest smartphone, it is also missing. So I had to use RTL-SDR V3 and GQRX as a control receiver, the result is on CDRV.

Of course, before testing it is necessary to choose a free frequency so that there are no stations on it, and it is advisable not to exceed the allowed power. For those who want to get the maximum range, you can buy an amplifier , it is desirable to make the antenna at the desired frequency, so that there is at least a 1/4 dipole wavelength.

Conclusion


As you can see, in principle, the transfer of FM radio is nothing too complicated, everything is quite realizable in GNU Radio (although it would be difficult to repeat this without the presence of examples, given that the system is not documented at all). Well now, at least, readers have a working example.
